solved[depIdx]--;\n        if (unresolved[depIdx] === 0) queue.push(depIdx);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return wires;\n}\n\nexport function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n  const pad = (i: number) => i.toString().padStart(2, '0');\n\n  // Build lookup: (op, sorted inputs) -> gate\n  const gateByInputs = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const inputs = gate.in1 < gate.in2 ? `${gate.in1},${gate.in2}` : `${gate.in2},${gate.in1}`;\n    gateByInputs.set(`${gate.op}:${inputs}`, gate);\n  }\n\n  // Build lookup: output wire -> gate\n  const gateByOutput = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    gateByOutput.set(gate.out, gate);\n  }\n\n  function lookup(op: string, w1: string, w2: string): Gate | undefined {\n    const inputs = w1 < w2 ? `${w1},${w2}` : `${w2},${w1}`;\n    return gateByInputs.get(`${op}:${inputs}`);\n  }\n\n  const swapped: Set<string> = new Set();\n\n  // Determine number of input bits\n  let numBits = 0;\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      const m = w.match(/^[xy](\\d+)$/);\n      if (m) numBits = Math.max(numBits, parseInt(m[1]) + 1);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Walk the adder structure bit by bit.\n  // We track the carry wire name as we go.\n  // Swaps only affect 'out' fields, so gate inputs still reference original wire names.\n\n  // For bit 0: half adder\n  //   XOR(x00, y00) -> should be z00\n  //   AND(x00, y00) -> carry_0 (any name)\n  const xor0 = lookup('XOR', 'x00', 'y00');\n  let carry = '';\n\n  if (xor0) {\n    if (xor0.out !== 'z00') {\n      swapped.add(xor0.out);\n      swapped.add('z00');\n    }\n  }\n\n  const and0 = lookup('AND', 'x00', 'y00');\n  if (and0) {\n    carry = and0.out;\n    // Carry could have been swapped with a z-wire. We'll detect that\n    // if it causes downstream issues. But we can also check: if carry\n    // starts with 'z', it's likely swapped. However, we need a more\n    // principled approach.\n  }\n\n  // For bits 1..N-1: full adder\n  for (let i = 1; i < numBits; i++) {\n    const xi = `x${pad(i)}`, yi = `y${pad(i)}`, zi = `z${pad(i)}`;\n\n    // XOR(xi, yi) -> partial_sum\n    const xorGate = lookup('XOR', xi, yi);\n    if (!xorGate) continue;\n    let partialSum = xorGate.out;\n\n    // XOR(partialSum, carry) -> should be zi\n    let sumGate = lookup('XOR', partialSum, carry);\n\n    // If sumGate not found, it might be because partialSum or carry was swapped.\n    // Check if partialSum was swapped: if gateByOutput has something that uses\n    // the expected pattern, or we need to try alternatives.\n    if (!sumGate) {\n      // partialSum might have been swapped. The real partial sum wire is\n      // what some XOR gate uses along with carry. Let's check: is there a\n      // gate that takes carry as input and is an XOR?\n      // Actually, the simplest approach: if the XOR gate's output was swapped,\n      // then partialSum is the wrong wire name. The gate that SHOULD use\n      // partialSum actually uses the wire that was swapped IN.\n      //\n      // Since we can look up by output: the wire that the xorGate SHOULD\n      // have produced is now on some other gate. That other gate's output\n      // is what xorGate has (they were swapped).\n      //\n      // Let's try: look for a XOR gate that has carry as one input. If its\n      // other input is something that isn't partialSum, that other input might\n      // be the correct wire and partialSum was swapped with it.\n\n      // Try: maybe carry was swapped. Look for XOR gate with partialSum as input.\n      // We'd need to search all gates. Let's build a helper.\n\n      // Alternative approach: check if partialSum is a z-wire (it shouldn't be)\n      // or if carry is a z-wire (it shouldn't be for intermediate bits).\n      // If partialSum looks wrong, the xorGate.out was swapped.\n\n      // Actually, let's think about this differently. If partialSum was swapped\n      // with wire W, then:\n      // - xorGate.out = W (wrong, should be partialSum's original name)\n      // - Some other gate that should output W now outputs the original partialSum name\n      // - The downstream XOR gate has in1/in2 pointing to the original wire names\n      //   (before swaps), which means it references the TRUE partialSum wire name\n      //   (which is now on the other gate, not xorGate)\n      //\n      // Wait - this is the key: in1/in2 reference the ACTUAL wire names in the\n      // circuit. Swaps only change 'out'. So if gate A should output 'foo' but\n      // now outputs 'bar' (swapped), and gate B has in1='foo', then gate B\n      // references 'foo' which is now produced by the OTHER swapped gate.\n      //\n      // So when I look up XOR(partialSum, carry), I'm using xorGate.out as\n      // partialSum. But xorGate.out might be wrong (swapped). The downstream\n      // gate's in1/in2 still reference the TRUE wire names (the unswapped ones).\n      //\n      // So I need to figure out what the TRUE partial sum wire name is.\n      // If xorGate.out was swapped from 'foo' to 'bar', then the TRUE partial\n      // sum is 'foo', and some other gate now has out='foo'.\n      //\n      // I can detect this: look for any XOR gate where one input is carry and\n      // the other input is NOT partialSum. That other input is the TRUE partial sum.\n\n      for (const g of gates) {\n        if (g.op !== 'XOR') continue;\n        if (g.in1 === carry || g.in2 === carry) {\n          const other = g.in1 === carry ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n          if (other !== partialSum) {\n            // partialSum was swapped with 'other'\n            // xorGate.out = partialSum (wrong), should be 'other'\n            // some other gate has out = 'other' (wrong), should be partialSum's name\n            swapped.add(partialSum);\n            swapped.add(other);\n            partialSum = other;\n            sumGate = g;\n            break;\n          }\n        }\n      }\n\n      // If still not found,